ome invasions in film]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award for Best Foreign Film winners]]\n[[Category:Korean-language films]]\n[[Category:Madman Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Neon (distributor) films]]\n[[Category:Palme d'Or winners]]\n[[Category:South Korean black comedy films]]\n[[Category:South Korean films]]\n[[Category:South Korean thriller films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 South Korean dark comedy thriller film directed by Bong Joon-ho}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Parasite\n| image          = Parasite (2019 film).png\n| alt            = The Official Poster of Parasite.\n| caption        = South Korean theatrical release poster\n| film name      = {{Film name\n| hangul = \uae30\uc0dd\ucda9\n| hanja = \u5bc4\u751f\u87f2\n| rr = Gisaengchung\n| mr = Kisaengch'ung\n| translation = }}\n| director       = [[Bong Joon-ho]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kwak Sin-ae]]\n* Moon Yang-kwon\n* Bong Joon-ho\n* Jang Young-hwan\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Bong Joon-ho\n* [[Han Jin-won]]\n}}\n| story          = Bong Joon-ho<ref name=press>{{cite web |title=''Parasite'' international press kit |url=https://cdn-media.festival-cannes.com/film_film/0001/66/72f026493fedd9576b0ebc4b7837fd67b8cc95a3.pdf |publisher=[[CJ Entertainment]] |access-date=1 January 2020 |date=2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110043736/https://cdn-media.festival-cannes.com/film_film/0001/66/72f026493fedd9576b0ebc4b7837fd67b8cc95a3.pdf |archive-date=10 January 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Song Kang-ho]]\n* [[Lee Sun-kyun]]\n* [[Cho Yeo-jeong]]\n* [[Choi Woo-shik]]\n* [[Park So-dam]]\n* [[Lee Jung-eun (actress)|Lee Jung-eun]]\n* [[Jang Hye-jin (actress)|Jang Hye-jin]]\n<!-- Per South Korean poster billing -->\n}}\n| music          = Jung Jae-il<ref name=press />\n| cinematography = [[Hong Kyung-pyo]]<ref>{{cite web |title=BONG Joon-ho's ''PARASITE'' Claims Early Sales |url=https://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=1&blbdComCd=601006&seq=5013&mode=VIEW |website=Korean Film Biz Zone |access-date=3 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204013817/https://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=1&blbdComCd=601006&seq=5013&mode=VIEW |archive-date=4 February 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| editing        = [[Yang Jin-mo]]\n| studio         = Barunson E&A<ref name=press />\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[CJ Entertainment]]\n }}\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2019|5|21|[[2019 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2019|5|30|South Korea}}\n| runtime        = 132 minutes<ref name=Cannes>{{cite web |title=''GISAENGCHUNG'' \u2013 Festival de Cannes 2019 |url=https://www.festival-cannes.com/en/festival/films/gisaengchung |publisher=[[Cannes Film Festival]] |access-date=1 January 2020 |date=2019 |quote=Country : SOUTH KOREA/Length : 132 minutes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903091243/http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/festival/films/gisaengchung |archive-date=3 September 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Naver />\n| country        = South Korea<ref name=press /><ref name=Cannes />\n| language       = Korean\n| budget         = {{KRW|13.5 billion}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hankyung.com/entertainment/article/2019060326461 |date=3 June 2019|script-title=ko:\uc601\ud654 '\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9' \ud765\ud589 \uc9c8\uc8fc...\uc190\uc775\ubd84\uae30\uc810 400\ub9cc\uba85 \ub208\uc55e |title=Archived copy|access-date=26 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626173250/https://www.hankyung.com/entertainment/article/2019060326461|archive-date=26 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><br />{{nowrap|(~US$11.4 million)}}\n| gross          = $266 million<ref name=\"NUM\" /><ref name=\"BOM\" />\n}}\n\n'''''Parasite''''' ({{ko-hhrm|\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9||Gisaengchung}}) is a 2019 South Korean [[black comedy]] [[thriller film]] directed by [[Bong Joon-ho]], who also co-wrote the screenplay with [[Han Jin-won]]. It stars [[Song Kang-ho]], [[Lee Sun-kyun]], [[Cho Yeo-jeong]], [[Choi Woo-shik]], [[Park So-dam]], [[Jang Hye-jin (actress)|Jang Hye-jin]], and [[Lee Jung-eun (actress)|Lee Jung-eun]] and follows the members of a poor family who scheme to become employed by a wealthy family by infiltrating their household and posing as unrelated, highly qualified individuals.\n\n''Parasite'' premiered at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival]] on 21 May 2019, where it became the first South Korean film to win the [[Palme d'Or]]. It was then released in South Korea by [[CJ Entertainment]] on 30 May 2019.\n\nThe film received universal critical acclaim, with praise directed towards its screenplay, Bong's direction, acting, social commentary, dark humor, cinematography, editing and production values, and has featured in multiple listings of the best films of the 2010s and is considered one of the [[List of films considered the best|best South Korean films of all time]]. It grossed over $266 million worldwide on a production budget of about $11 million, becoming [[List of highest-grossing films in South Korea#Domestic films by gross|the highest-grossing South Korean film]].\n\nAmong its [[List of accolades received by Parasite|numerous accolades]], ''Parasite'' won a leading four awards at the [[92nd Academy Awards]]: [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], and [[Academy Award for Best International Feature Film|Best International Feature Film]]. It became the first South Korean film to receive Academy Award recognition, as well as the first film not in English to win Best Picture.{{refn|group=note|Although ''Parasite'' was the first film not in English to win Best Picture at the Oscars, it is not to be confused with the first   ''foreign'' film (produced by a company of a country that does not have English as its primary language) to win Best Picture, which was achieved by ''[[The Artist (film)|The Artist]]'' in 2012. The French-produced film was largely silent with French [[intertitle]]s and contained a few spoken lines in English.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Artist|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1655442/|access-date=10 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113030121/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1655442/|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Academy dictates foreign language as the main qualification for international film, hence ''The Artist'' did not qualify.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/rules-eligibility|title=Rules & Eligibility|date=28 July 2014|website=Oscars.org {{!}} Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|language=en|access-date=10 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108163338/https://www.oscars.org/oscars/rules-eligibility|archive-date=8 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>}} It also won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film]] and the [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language]], and became the first film not in English to win the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]].\n\n== Plot ==\nThe Kim family \u2013 father Ki-taek, mother Chung-sook, daughter Ki-jung and son Ki-woo \u2013 live in a small semi-[[basement apartment]] (''banjiha''),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kim |first1=Victoria |title=The halfway underground homes of 'Parasite' are real spaces of desperation and dreams |url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-12/movie-parasite-korea-bong-joon-ho-banjiha |website=Los Angeles Times |access-date=13 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212185826/https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-12/movie-parasite-korea-bong-joon-ho-banjiha |archive-date=12 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> have low-paying temporary jobs as pizza box folders, and struggle to make ends meet.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Park |first1=S. Nathan |title='Parasite' Has a Hidden Backstory of Middle-Class Failure and Chicken Joints |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/21/korea-bong-oscars-parasite-hidden-backstory-middle-class-chicken-bong-joon-ho/ |accessdate=26 February 2020 |work=Foreign Policy |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225172736/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/21/korea-bong-oscars-parasite-hidden-backstory-middle-class-chicken-bong-joon-ho/ |archive-date=25 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> University student Min-hyuk, a friend of Ki-woo's, gives the family a [[Suseok|scholar's rock]] meant to promise wealth. Leaving to study abroad, he suggests that Ki-woo takes over his job as an English [[tutor]] for the wealthy Park family, though Ki-woo is initially hesitant. Ki-jung forges a diploma from [[Yonsei University]] for Ki-woo to help him get hired; upon arrival, Mrs. Park decides they will call him \"Kevin\".\n\nThe Kim family infiltrates the lives of the Parks by recommending each other's services, posing as unrelated and highly qualified workers. Ki-woo tutors and begins a romance with the Parks' daughter, Da-hye. Ki-jung poses as \"Jessica\", an [[Art therapy|art therapist]] to the Parks' hyperactive young son, Da-song. Ki-jung frames Mr. Park's chauffeur as having had [[sex]] in the car by leaving her underwear beneath the passenger seat for Mr. Park to discover, and Ki-taek is hired to replace him. Finally, Chung-sook takes over as the Parks' housekeeper after the Kims exploit the severe peach [[allergy]] of the long-time housekeeper, Moon-gwang, and convince Mrs. Park that she has [[tuberculosis]].\n\nWhen the Parks leave on a camping trip for Da-song's birthday, the Kims revel in the luxuries of the Park residence. Moon-gwang returns, telling Chung-sook she has left something in the house's basement, and reveals the hidden entrance to an [[Bunker|underground bunker]] created by the house's architect and previous owner. Moon-gwang's husband, Geun-sae, has been secretly living underneath the home for years, hiding from [[loan shark]]s after his [[Taiwan|Taiwanese]] [[bakery]] failed and left him in huge debt. Chung-sook refuses Moon-gwang's pleas to help Geun-sae remain in the bunker, but the eavesdropping Kims accidentally reveal to Moon-gwang the truth about them.\n\nA severe rainstorm brings the Parks home early, and the Kims scramble to clean up the home before the Parks return, while a brawl breaks out between Moon-gwang, Geun-sae, and the Kims. The Kims trap Geun-sae and a mortally wounded Moon-gwang in the bunker, and Ki-taek sees Geun-sae sending a fruitless message in [[SKATS|Morse code]] using the home's lights. Mrs. Park reveals to Chung-sook that Da-song had a [[seizure]]-inducing [[Psychological trauma|traumatic experience]] on a previous birthday when he saw a \"ghost\" \u2013 actually Geun-sae emerging from the basement \u2013 and that the family has celebrated Da-song's birthday outside the house ever since. The Kims escape the Parks' house unseen, but not before hearing Mr. Park's offhand comment that Ki-taek, despite being a good employee, smells bad. Returning home to find their apartment completely flooded by the storm, the Kims are forced to sleep in a gymnasium with other displaced people.\n\nThe next day, Mrs. Park hosts a house party for Da-song's birthday, with the Kim family in attendance. Ki-woo enters the bunker with the scholar's rock to face Geun-sae. Finding Moon-gwang dead, he is attacked by Geun-sae, who bludgeons him with the rock and escapes. Seeking to avenge Moon-gwang, Geun-sae stabs Ki-jung with a kitchen knife in front of the horrified guests. Da-song suffers another seizure upon seeing Geun-sae, and a struggle breaks out until Chung-sook fatally impales Geun-sae with a barbecue skewer. While Ki-taek tends to a severely bleeding Ki-jung, Mr. Park orders him to drive Da-song to the hospital. In the chaos, Ki-taek, upon seeing Mr. Park's disgusted reaction to Geun-sae's smell, takes the knife and kills Mr. Park before fleeing the scene.\n\nWeeks later, Ki-woo wakes up after brain surgery. He and Chung-sook are convicted of [[fraud]] and put on probation. Ki-jung has died from her injury and Ki-taek, wanted for Mr. Park's murder, has vanished. Geun-sae's motives for the attack are a mystery to the public. Ki-woo watches the Parks' home, which has been sold to a German family unaware of its history and sees a message in Morse code from the flickering lights. It is from Ki-taek, who escaped into the bunker and now survives by scavenging from the new homeowners. Still living in the banjiha with his mother, Ki-woo writes a letter to Ki-taek, vowing to earn enough money to one day purchase the house and free his father.\n\n== Cast ==\nThe romanisation of the names of characters are as appeared in the official English subtitles, translated by [[Darcy Paquet]].\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Song Kang-ho]] as Kim Ki-taek ({{Korean|hangul=\uae40\uae30\ud0dd|rr=Gim Gitaek|labels=no}}), father of the Kim family\n* [[Choi Woo-shik]] as Kim Ki-woo (Kevin; {{Korean|hangul=\uae40\uae30\uc6b0|rr=Gim Giu|labels=no}}), son of the Kim family\n* [[Park So-dam]] as Kim Ki-jung (Jessica; {{Korean|hangul=\uae40\uae30\uc815|rr=Gim Gijeong|labels=no}}), daughter of the Kim family\n* [[Jang Hye-jin (actress)|Jang Hye-jin]] as Park<!-- Not Kim, as Korean women don't follow their husbands' names after marriage. --> Chung-sook ({{Korean|hangul=\ubc15\ucda9\uc219|rr=Bak Chungsuk|labels=no}}), mother of the Kim family\n* [[Lee Sun-kyun]] as Park Dong-ik (Nathan; {{Korean|hangul=\ubc15\ub3d9\uc775|rr=Bak Dongik|labels=no}}), father of the Park family\n* [[Cho Yeo-jeong]] as Choi Yeon-gyo ({{Korean|hangul=\ucd5c\uc5f0\uad50|rr=Choe Yeongyo|labels=no}}), mother of the Park family\n* [[Jung Ji-so]] as Park Da-hye ({{Korean|hangul=\ubc15\ub2e4\ud61c|rr=Bak Dahye|labels=no}}), daughter of the Park family\n* [[Jung Hyeon-jun]] as Park Da-song ({{Korean|hangul=\ubc15\ub2e4\uc1a1|rr=Bak Dasong|labels=no}}), son of the Park family\n* [[Lee Jung-eun (actress)|Lee Jung-eun]] as Gook Moon-gwang ({{Korean|hangul=\uad6d\ubb38\uad11|rr=Guk Mungwang|labels=no}}), the housekeeper\n* [[Park Myung-hoon]] as Oh Geun-sae ({{Korean|hangul=\uc624\uadfc\uc138|rr=O Geunse|labels=no}}), Moon-gwang's husband\n* Park Geun-rok as Yoon ({{Korean|hangul=\uc724|rr=Yun|labels=no}}), Kim Ki-taek's predecessor as Park Dong-ik's chauffeur\n* [[Park Seo-joon]] as Min-hyuk ({{Korean|hangul=\ubbfc\ud601|rr=Minhyeok|labels=no}}), Ki-woo's friend (cameo appearance)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Park |first1=Boram |title='Rom-com master' Park Seo-joon embraces career-changing role in action horror film |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20190725009700315 |accessdate=2 March 2020 |agency=[[Yonhap News Agency]] |date=25 July 2019 |language=en}}<!-- Note that the English report is basically a translation of the original interview in Korean [https://www.yna.co.kr/view/AKR20190724141500005], but the Korean one does not mention Park Seo-joon's cameo appearance in Parasite (unlike the English version). --></ref>\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\nThe idea for ''Parasite'' originated in 2013. While working on ''[[Snowpiercer]]'', Bong was encouraged by a theatre actor friend to write a play. He had been a tutor for the son of a wealthy family in Seoul in his early 20s, and considered turning his experience into a stage production.<ref name =\"THRBrzeski\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/making-parasite-how-bong-joon-hos-real-life-inspired-a-plot-twisty-tale-rich-poor-1252015|title=Making of 'Parasite': How Bong Joon Ho's Real Life Inspired a Plot-Twisty Tale of Rich vs. Poor|last=Brzeski|first=Patrick|date=8 November 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=18 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113115829/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/making-parasite-how-bong-joon-hos-real-life-inspired-a-plot-twisty-tale-rich-poor-1252015|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The film's title, ''Parasite'', was selected by Bong as it served a double meaning, which he had to convince the film's marketing group to use. Bong said \"Because the story is about the poor family infiltrating and creeping into the rich house, it seems very obvious that ''Parasite'' refers to the poor family, and I think that's why the marketing team was a little hesitant. But if you look at it the other way, you can say that rich family, they're also parasites in terms of labor. They can't even wash dishes, they can't drive themselves, so they leech off the poor family's labor. So both are parasites.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/parasite-bong-joon-ho-reveals-the-meaning-behind-the-title-of-the-oscar-nominated-film |title=Parasite: Bong Joon-ho Reveals the Meaning Behind the Title of the Oscar-Nominated Film |first=Adele |last=Ankers |date=31 January 2020 |access-date=31 January 2020 |work=[[IGN]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200131150546/https://www.ign.com/articles/parasite-bong-joon-ho-reveals-the-meaning-behind-the-title-of-the-oscar-nominated-film | archive-date = 31 January 2020 | url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n=== Writing ===\nAfter completing ''Snowpiercer'', Bong wrote a 15-page [[film treatment]] for the first half of ''Parasite'', which his production assistant on ''Snowpiercer'', Han Jin-won, turned into three different drafts of the screenplay.<ref name =\"THRBrzeski\" /> After finishing ''[[Okja]]'', Bong returned to the project and finished the script; Han received credit as a co-writer.<ref name =\"THRBrzeski\" />\n\nBong said the film was influenced by the 1960 Korean \"domestic Gothic\" film ''[[The Housemaid (1960 film)|The Housemaid]]'' in which a middle-class family's stability is threatened by the arrival of a disruptive interloper in the form of household help.<ref name=\"NPR1\">{{Cite news |last=Ulaby |first=Neda |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/10/785090210/parasite-director-bong-joon-ho-wanted-to-reflect-the-truth-of-current-times |title='Parasite' Director Bong Joon-ho 'Wanted To Reflect The Truth Of Current Times |date=10 December 2019 |work=[[NPR]] |access-date=12 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191212221503/https://www.npr.org/2019/12/10/785090210/parasite-director-bong-joon-ho-wanted-to-reflect-the-truth-of-current-times |archive-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> The incident of [[Christine and L\u00e9a Papin]]\u2014two live-in maids who murdered their employers in 1930s France\u2014also served as a source of inspiration to Bong.<ref name=\"JungEA\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/parasite-ending-explained-by-bong-joon-ho.html |title=Bong Joon Ho on Why He Wanted ''Parasite'' to End With a 'Surefire Kill' |last=Jung, E. Alex |date=14 January 2020 |website=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115024246/https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/parasite-ending-explained-by-bong-joon-ho.html |archive-date=15 January 2020 |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> Bong also considered his own past, where he had tutored for a rich family. Bong said \"I got this feeling that I was infiltrating the private lives of complete strangers. Every week I would go into their house, and I thought how fun it would be if I could get all my friends to infiltrate the house one by one.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/10/bong-joon-ho-parasite-interview/600007/ |title=How Bong Joon Ho Invented the Weird World of Parasite |last=Sims |first=David |date=15 October 2019 |website=[[The Atlantic]] |access-date=16 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217011351/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/10/bong-joon-ho-parasite-interview/600007/ |archive-date=17 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Additionally, the element of Moon-gwang having an allergy to [[peaches]] was inspired by one of Bong's university friends having this allergy, as Bong confirmed in a [[Reddit]] [[/r/IAmA|AMA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://old.reddit.com/r/movies/comments/drqrii/im_bong_joon_ho_director_of_parasite_ama/f6kqvqe/|title=One of my college friends had a peach allergy. We all thought he was joking, and bought a peach to throw at him, and his entire body turned red. It was all very shocking, and we felt very bad. But I didn't throw the peach! It wasn't me!!|publisher=[[Reddit]]|accessdate=2020-01-23}} - Verified [[Reddit]] account of director Bong</ref> Another notable character element comes from Ki-woo and his inability to perform well in university examinations. Choi Woo-shik, who plays Ki-woo, stated that the character is intelligent, yet he does not have the \"vigor\" needed to succeed in examinations.<ref name=HarrisChoiInt>{{cite web |author=Harris, Hunter |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/10/parasite-movie-choi-woo-shik-bong-joon-ho-ending.html |title=''Parasite''{{'}}s Choi Woo-shik Is Optimistic About the Movie's Overwhelming Ending|work=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]|date=16 October 2019|access-date=23 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209182409/https://www.vulture.com/2019/10/parasite-movie-choi-woo-shik-bong-joon-ho-ending.html|archive-date=9 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ki-woo himself tells Da-hye that she needs that quality to pass examinations.<ref name=HarrisChoiInt/>\n\n[[Darcy Paquet]], an American residing in South Korea, served as translator for the English subtitles and worked directly with Bong.<ref name=Hanweaving>{{cite web |author=Han, Karen |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/10/14/20906430/parasite-bong-joon-ho-interview-rock-peach-spoilers |title=Bong Joon-ho on weaving his personal memories into Parasite |work=[[Polygon (magazine)|Polygon]] |date=14 October 2019 |access-date=9 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226230904/https://www.polygon.com/2019/10/14/20906430/parasite-bong-joon-ho-interview-rock-peach-spoilers|archive-date=26 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Paquet rendered Jjapaguri or Chapaguri (\uc9dc\ud30c\uad6c\ub9ac), a dish cooked by a character in the film, as ''ram-don'', meaning [[ramen]]-[[udon]]. It is a mix of [[Chapagetti]] and [[Neoguri (instant noodle)|Neoguri]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Rochlin, Margy |url=https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2019-10-19/parasite-ramdon-bong-joon-ho-ramen-udon-jjapaguri |title=How steak and 'ramdon' illustrate class tensions in Bong Joon Ho's 'Parasite' |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=19 October 2019 |access-date=24 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115132532/https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2019-10-19/parasite-ramdon-bong-joon-ho-ramen-udon-jjapaguri|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The English version of the film shows packages labelled in English \"[[ramyeon]]\" and \"udon\" to highlight to English speakers how the name was created. Paquet believed the word ''ram-don'' did not previously exist as he found no results on Google.<ref name=LeeHanaParasub>{{cite web |author=Lee, Hana |url=http://m.korea.net/english/NewsFocus/People/view?articleId=171974&page=1 |title='Parasite' subtitle translator: Comedies are a fun challenge |work=[[Korea.net]] |date=19 June 2019 |access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208155256/http://m.korea.net/english/NewsFocus/People/view?articleId=171974&page=1|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On one occasion, Paquet used [[Oxford University]] as a reference instead of [[Seoul National University]], and in another, used [[WhatsApp]] as the messaging application instead of [[KakaoTalk]].<ref name=Hanweaving /> Paquet chose Oxford over [[Harvard University]] because of Bong's affinity for the United Kingdom, and because Paquet believed using Harvard would be \"too obvious a choice.\"<ref name=LeeHanaParasub /> Paquet wrote, \"[I]n order for humor to work, people need to understand it immediately. With an unfamiliar word, the humor is lost.\"<ref name=LeeHanaParasub />\n\nFollowing the release of the film, on 16 February 2020, Indian film producer [[P. L. Thenappan]] challenged the originality of the film script and threatened to take legal action against the makers of ''Parasite'' for \"story theft\" against his 1999 [[Tamil language|Tamil]] film ''[[Minsara Kanna]]''. The allegation did not receive significant ongoing attention in the media and has not yet been adjudicated in a court.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/pl-thenappan-awaits-response-to-the-intimation-mail-sent-to-parasite-team/articleshow/74193541.cms |title=PL Thenappan awaits response to the intimation mail sent to Parasite team |last=Menon |first=Thinkal |date=19 February 2020 |website=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=20 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220201705/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/pl-thenappan-awaits-response-to-the-intimation-mail-sent-to-parasite-team/articleshow/74193541.cms |archive-date=20 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/parasite-plagiarism-row-minsara-kanna-producer-pl-thenappan-sends-intimation-mail-1647884-2020-02-19 |title=Parasite plagiarism row: Minsara Kanna producer PL Thenappan sends intimation mail |date=19 February 2020 |website=[[India Today]] |access-date=20 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220015938/https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/parasite-plagiarism-row-minsara-kanna-producer-pl-thenappan-sends-intimation-mail-1647884-2020-02-19 |archive-date=20 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Parasite house before and after VFX.jpg|thumb|left|The house was constructed on a set and everything above the first floor was added in post-production.]]\nPrincipal photography for ''Parasite'' began on 18 May 2018<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kil |first1=Sonia |title=Bong Joon-ho's ''Parasite'' Starts Shooting (EXCLUSIVE) |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/bong-joon-ho-parasite-shooting-1202825038/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=3 February 2019 |language=en |date=30 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430121851/https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/bong-joon-ho-parasite-shooting-1202825038/ |archive-date=30 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bong Joon-ho's ''Parasite'' Enters Production |url=https://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=2&blbdComCd=601006&seq=4849&mode=VIEW |website=Korean Film Biz Zone |access-date=3 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626230323/https://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=2&blbdComCd=601006&seq=4849&mode=VIEW |archive-date=26 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and ended 124 days later on 19 September 2018.<ref name=\"release\">{{cite web |title=Bong Joon-ho's ''Parasite'' Wraps Production |url=https://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=1&blbdComCd=601006&seq=5001&mode=VIEW |website=Korean Film Biz Zone |access-date=3 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204014147/https://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=1&blbdComCd=601006&seq=5001&mode=VIEW |archive-date=4 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Filming took place around [[Seoul]] and in [[Jeonju]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.screendaily.com/features/bong-joon-ho-talks-parasite-it-deals-with-polarisation/5139556.article |title=Bong Joon Ho talks 'Parasite': \"It deals with polarisation\" |website=[[Screen International|Screen Daily]] |date=30 June 2019 |access-date=18 January 2020 |last=Noh |first=Jean |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190727005536/https://www.screendaily.com/features/bong-joon-ho-talks-parasite-it-deals-with-polarisation/5139556.article |archive-date = 27 July 2019 |url-status = live}}</ref> The director of photography for the film is [[Hong Kyung-pyo]].\n\nThe Parks' house was a specially constructed set. The first floor and the garden were constructed on an empty outdoor lot, while the basement and second floor were constructed on set.<ref name=\"archdigest\"/> \"We built the main floor of the house in a backlot and for the second floor it was all green screen outside,\" explained editor [[Yang Jin-mo]]. \"When we shot toward the outside from inside, everything beyond the garden was all VFX.\"<ref name=\"Frame.io Insider 2020\">{{cite web | title=How Parasite Uses Brilliant Design and Invisible VFX to Transcend Language | website=Frame.io Insider | date=2020-01-13 | url=https://blog.frame.io/2020/01/13/parasite-design-and-vfx/ | access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\nBong, as part of the scripting, had also designed the basic layout of this home. \"It's like its own universe inside this film. Each character and each team has spaces that they take over that they can infiltrate, and also secret spaces that they don't know.\"<ref name=\"IndieWire 2019\" /> A fictional architect Namgoong Hyeonja had been introduced as the home's designer and the previous owner before the Parks, and production designer Lee Ha-jun considered the function and form of the house based on how Namgoong would have designed it.<ref name=\"archdigest\"/>\n\nLee said, \"Since Mr Park's house is built by an architect in the story, it wasn't easy finding the right approach to designing the house...I'm not an architect, and I think there's a difference in how an architect envisions a space and how a production designer does. We prioritize blocking and camera angles while architects build spaces for people to actually live in and thus design around people. So I think the approach is very different.\"<ref name=\"IndieWire 2019\" /> For example, Ha-jun established that Namgoong would have used the first floor's living room to appreciate the garden, so it was built with a single wide window and only spartan seating options for this function.<ref name=\"archdigest\"/> Some of the interior artwork in the house sets were by South Korea artist Seung-mo Park, including existing artwork of hers and some explicitly created for the film.<ref name=\"archdigest\"/> Further, design of the home and of its interiors were aimed to make the set amenable for filming at the 2.35:1 aspect ratio, favoring wide and deeper rooms rather than height.<ref name=\"IndieWire 2019\" />\n\nLee said the sun was an important factor when building the outdoor set. \"The sun's direction was a crucial point of consideration while we were searching for outdoor lots,\" explained Lee. \"We had to remember the sun's position during our desired time frame and determine the positions and sizes of the windows accordingly. In terms of practical lighting, the DP [director of photography Hong Kyung-pyo] had specific requests regarding the color. He wanted sophisticated indirect lighting and the warmth from [[Incandescent light bulb|tungsten light sources]]. Before building the set, the DP and I visited the lot several times to check the sun's movement at each time, and we decided on the set's location together.\"<ref name=\"IndieWire 2019\">{{cite web |title=How Bong Joon Ho Designed the House in ''Parasite'' |website=[[IndieWire]] |date=29 October 2019 |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/10/parasite-house-set-design-bong-joon-ho-1202185829/ |access-date=6 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104232715/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/10/parasite-house-set-design-bong-joon-ho-1202185829/ |archive-date=4 November 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Set design ===\nThe Kim's semi-basement apartment and its street was also built on set, partially out of necessity for filming the flooding scenes.<ref name=\"IndieWire 2019\" /> Lee Ha-jun visited and photographed several abandoned villages and towns in South Korea scheduled to be torn down to help inform the set design. He also created stories for the Kim's neighbors and added details of those residents along the street to improve the authenticity of the street's appearance.<ref name=\"archdigest\">{{cite web | url = https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/bong-joon-ho-parasite-movie-set-design-interview | title = Inside the House From Bong Joon Ho's Parasite | first = Rachel | last = Wallace | date = 31 October 2019 | accessdate = 16 February 2020 | work = [[Architectural Digest]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191106032043/https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/bong-joon-ho-parasite-movie-set-design-interview | archive-date = 6 November 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n=== Editing ===\nAccording to editor [[Yang Jin-mo]], Bong Joon-ho chose to shoot the film without traditional [[Camera coverage|coverage]]. To give them more editing options with limited shots, they sometimes stitched together different takes of the same shot.<ref>{{cite web |last=Buder |first=Emily |title='Parasite' Editor Jinmo Yang Teaches Us How to Edit Without Coverage |url=https://nofilmschool.com/parasite-editor-interview |website=No Film School |date=6 December 2019 |access-date=17 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200118035230/https://nofilmschool.com/parasite-editor-interview |archive-date=18 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe principal release and editing of the film was done for release in color. A [[black and white]] version of the film was produced prior to the world premiere in Cannes and debuted on 26 January 2020 at the [[International Film Festival Rotterdam]] and was rescreened from 29 to 31 January. It also received a limited release in some countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://iffr.com/en/2020/films/parasite-bw-version |title=Parasite (B&W Version) |work=IFFR.com |access-date=13 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209090234/https://iffr.com/en/2020/films/parasite-bw-version |archive-date=9 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bong-joon-ho-black-white-parasite-cut-1274862 |title=Bong Joon Ho Talks Genesis of New Black-and-White 'Parasite' Cut |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Alex |last=Ritman |date=30 January 2020 |access-date=13 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213155204/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bong-joon-ho-black-white-parasite-cut-1274862 |archive-date=13 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Parasite: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = Jung Jae-il\n| cover        =\n| alt          = \n| released     = 30 May 2019\n| recorded     = 2019\n| genre        = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length       = 52:14\n| language     = [[Korean language|Korean]]\n| label        = {{hlist|[[Genie Music]]|[[Stone Music Entertainment]]}}\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Parasite: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n | type        = soundtrack\n | single1     = Soju One Glass\n | single1date = 30 May 2019\n}}\n}}\nThe film's [[Film score|score]] was written by South Korean composer Jung Jae-il, who also wrote the score for Bong Joon-ho's 2017 film ''[[Okja]]''. Jung's music for ''Parasite'' consists of \"minimalist piano pieces, punctuated with light percussion,\" which sets the film's \"tense atmosphere.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.classicfm.com/discover-music/periods-genres/film-tv/parasite-music-soundtrack-italian-song-jung-jae-il/|title=Parasite film soundtrack: What's that Italian song and how can I listen to the score?|last=Pentreath|first=Rosie|date=10 February 2020|website=Classic FM|url-status=live|access-date=16 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216125628/https://www.classicfm.com/discover-music/periods-genres/film-tv/parasite-music-soundtrack-italian-song-jung-jae-il/|archive-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> Excerpts from [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]]'s opera ''[[Rodelinda (opera)|Rodelinda]]'' and the 1964 Italian song \"In ginocchio da te\" by [[Gianni Morandi]] also appear in the film.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe end credits song \"{{Transl|ko|RR|Soju han jan|italic=no}}\" ({{Lang-ko|\uc18c\uc8fc \ud55c \uc794|lit=A glass of [[soju]]}}; not to be confused with an unrelated song with same Korean title by [[Im Chang-jung]]) was written by Bong and is performed by [[Choi Woo-shik]], who also played the main character Ki-woo.<ref name=\"Forbes-19DEC17-SojuShortlist\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/joanmacdonald/2019/12/17/bong-joon-hos-glass-of-soju-nominated-for-oscar-song-shortlist/#60d3425c158c|title=Bong Joon-ho's 'Glass of Soju' nominated for Oscar Song Shortlist|last=MacDonald|first=Joan|date=17 December 2019|website=[[Forbes]]|url-status=live|access-date=16 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223164913/https://www.forbes.com/sites/joanmacdonald/2019/12/17/bong-joon-hos-glass-of-soju-nominated-for-oscar-song-shortlist/#60d3425c158c|archive-date=23 December 2019}}</ref> It is displayed in English as \"Soju One Glass\"{{Sic}} in the international digital releases of the soundtrack. When the song made it to the December 2019 shortlist for the [[92nd Academy Awards]] in the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] category,<ref name=\"Forbes-19DEC17-SojuShortlist\" /> it was listed under a grammatically correct English title, \"A Glass of Soju\".<ref>{{cite web |title=92nd OSCARS SHORTLISTS |url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/92nd-oscars-shortlists |publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] |accessdate=26 February 2020 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217011602/https://oscars.org/oscars/92nd-oscars-shortlists |archive-date=17 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe English titles of the scores listed below are as displayed in the back cover of the album and in the international digital releases of the soundtrack;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/2XRuEEbhMF9Q4TcJBw4GqP?si=XrCiwc7QTYylxS-AGymaHg|title=Parasite by Jung Jaeil|website=[[Spotify]]|url-status=live|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Parasite-Original-Motion-Picture-Soundtrack/dp/B07YVHQ929|title=Parasite (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)|website=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]|url-status=live|access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> the romanisation of names and nouns used are slightly different from those seen in the official English subtitles as translated by [[Darcy Paquet]].\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_music       =\n| headline = Original track list\n\n| title1 = Opening\n| note1 = {{Lang-ko|\uc2dc\uc791|lit=Start|label=none}}\n| length1 = 2:07\n\n| title2 = Conciliation I\n| length2 = 1:04\n| note2 = {{Lang-ko|\uccab\ubc88\uc9f8 \uc54c\uc120|lit=First conciliation|label=none}}\n\n| title3 = On the Way to Rich House\n| length3 = 0:55\n| note3 = {{Lang-ko|\ubd80\uc7a3\uc9d1 \uac00\ub294 \uae38|lit=On the way to the house of a wealthy family|label=none}}\n\n| title4 = Conciliation II\n| length4 = 1:10\n| note4 = {{Lang-ko|\ub450\ubc88\uc9f8 \uc54c\uc120|lit=Second conciliation|label=none}}\n\n| title5 = Plum Juice\n| length5 = 0:55\n| note5 = {{Lang-ko|\ub9e4\uc2e4\uccad|translit=[[Cheong (food)#Maesil-cheong|Maesilcheong]]|translit-std=RR|label=none}}\n\n| title6 = Mr. Yoon and Park\n| length6 = 1:51\n| note6 = {{Lang-ko|\uc724\uae30\uc0ac\uc640 \ubc15\uc0ac\uc7a5|lit=Chauffeur Yoon and President Park|label=none}}\n\n| title7 = Conciliation III\n| length7 = 1:17\n| note7 = {{Lang-ko|\uc138\ubc88\uc9f8 \uc54c\uc120|lit=Third conciliation|label=none}}\n\n| title8 = The Belt of Faith\n| length8 = 7:13\n| note8 = {{Lang-ko|\ubbff\uc74c\uc758 \ubca8\ud2b8|lit=Chain of trust|label=none}}\n\n| title9 = Moon Gwang Left\n| length9 = 0:56\n| note9 = {{Lang-ko|\ub5a0\ub098\ub294 \ubb38\uad11|lit=Moon-gwang leaving|label=none}}\n\n| title10 = Camping\n| length10 = 3:05\n| note10 = {{Lang-ko|\uc57c\uc601|label=none}}\n\n| title11 = The Hellgate\n| length11 = 1:15\n| note11 = {{Lang-ko|\uc9c0\uc625\uc758 \ubb38|lit=Gate of Hell|label=none}}\n\n| title12 = Heartrending Story of Bubu\n| length12 = 1:35\n| note12 = {{Lang-ko|\ubd80\ubd80\uc758 \uc0ac\uc5f0|lit=Story of a married couple|label=none}}\n\n| title13 = Zappaguri\n| length13 = 1:47\n| note13 = {{Lang-ko|\uc9dc\ud30c\uad6c\ub9ac|translit=Jjapaguri|translit-std=RR|label=none}}{{Efn|group=\"SoundtrackNote\"|{{transl|ko|RR|Jjapaguri}} refers to a mashup dish of instant noodles [[Chapagetti]] and [[Neoguri (instant noodle)|Neoguri]]. The name of the dish was translated as \"ramdon\" in the official English subtitles of the film.}}\n\n| title14 = Ghost\n| length14 = 2:00\n| note14 = {{Lang-ko|\uc720\ub839|label=none}}\n\n| title15 = The Family is Busy\n| length15 = 1:09\n| note15 = {{Lang-ko|\uccab\ubc88\uc9f8 \ub3d9\ubd84\uc11c\uc8fc|lit=First busyness|label=none}}\n\n| title16 = Busy to Survive\n| length16 = 1:53\n| note16 = {{Lang-ko|\ub450\ubc88\uc9f8 \ub3d9\ubd84\uc11c\uc8fc|lit=Second busyness|label=none}}\n\n| title17 = The Frontal Lobe of Ki Taek\n| length17 = 2:42\n| note17 = {{Lang-ko|\uae30\ud0dd\uc758 \uc804\ub450\uc5fd|label=none}}\n\n| title18 = Water, Ocean\n| length18 = 4:41\n| note18 = {{Lang-ko|\ubb3c\ubc14\ub2e4|lit=Flood|label=none}}\n\n| title19 = Water, Ocean Again\n| length19 = 1:36\n| note19 = {{Lang-ko|\ub610 \ubb3c\ubc14\ub2e4|lit=Flood again|label=none}}\n\n| title20 = It Is Sunday Morning\n| length20 = 4:03\n| note20 = {{Lang-ko|\uc77c\uc694\uc77c \uc544\uce68|lit=Sunday morning|label=none}}\n\n| title21 = Blood and Sword\n| length21 = 3:02\n| note21 = {{Lang-ko|\ud53c\uc640 \uce7c|lit=Blood and knife|label=none}}\n\n| title22 = Yasan\n| length22 = 1:15\n| note22 = {{Lang-ko|\uc57c\uc0b0|lit=[[Hillock]]|label=none}}\n\n| title23 = Moving\n| length23 = 1:44\n| note23 = {{Lang-ko|\uc774\uc0ac|label=none}}\n\n| title24 = Ending\n| length24 = 0:53\n| note24 = {{Lang-ko|\ub05d|lit=End|label=none}}\n\n| title25 = Soju One Glass\n| note25 = {{Lang-ko|\uc18c\uc8fc \ud55c \uc794|lit=A glass of [[soju]]|label=none}}; performed by [[Choi Woo-shik]]\n| length25 = 3:20\n\n|total_length = 52:14\n}}\n\n{{Notelist|group=\"SoundtrackNote\"}}\n\n== Themes and interpretations ==\nThe main themes of ''Parasite'' are [[class conflict]], [[social inequality]] and [[Economic inequality|wealth disparity]].<ref name=\"classconflict\">{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/05/776388423/the-hit-movie-parasite-puts-basement-structures-in-structural-inequality |title=The Hit Movie 'Parasite' Puts Basement Structures In Structural Inequality |date=5 November 2019 |access-date=3 February 2020 |last=Ulaby |first=Neda |publisher=[[NPR]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116002438/https://www.npr.org/2019/11/05/776388423/the-hit-movie-parasite-puts-basement-structures-in-structural-inequality|archive-date=16 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"hustlers\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/10/15/parasite-2019-cinematic-class-conflict/ |access-date=3 February 2020 |last=Holub |first=Christian |date=15 October 2019 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |title=From Parasite to Hustlers: How 2019 became the year of cinematic class conflict|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203170810/https://ew.com/movies/2019/10/15/parasite-2019-cinematic-class-conflict/|archive-date=3 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Film critics and Bong Joon-ho himself have considered the film as a reflection of [[late-stage capitalism]],<ref name=\"Bean\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/travisbean/2020/01/30/capitalism-gone-wild-the-ending-of-parasite-explained/#2a97c8df6dbd |title=Capitalism Gone Wild: The Ending of 'Parasite' Explained |last=Bean |first=Travis |date=30 January 2020 |access-date=3 February 2020 |work=[[Forbes]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131150417/https://www.forbes.com/sites/travisbean/2020/01/30/capitalism-gone-wild-the-ending-of-parasite-explained/#2a97c8df6dbd|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"capitalismGQ\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gq.com/story/parasite-director-bong-joon-ho-interview |title=Parasite Director Bong Joon-ho on the Art of Class Warfare |date=8 October 2019 |access-date=3 February 2020 |last=Paiella |first=Gabriella |work=[[GQ]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219211642/https://www.gq.com/story/parasite-director-bong-joon-ho-interview|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and some have associated it with the term \"[[Hell Joseon]]\", a phrase which has become popular, especially with young people, in the late 2010s to describe the difficulties of life in South Korea.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Minsoo |last1=Kim |access-date=7 February 2020 |title=Why \"Parasite\" Is Bong Joon-ho's Biggest Hit and Darkest Film Yet |url=https://www.cinemaescapist.com/2019/10/parasite-korean-movie-review/ |date=11 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111215042/https://www.cinemaescapist.com/2019/10/parasite-korean-movie-review/|archive-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Opinion: For South Korean youth, Parasite burrows close to home |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-for-south-korean-youth-parasite-burrows-close-to-home/ |via=The Globe and Mail |access-date=7 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110024738/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-for-south-korean-youth-parasite-burrows-close-to-home/|archive-date=10 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The film also analyses the use of \"connections\" to get ahead, especially for rich families<ref name=\"WBFO\">{{cite web |first1=Kelly |last1=Kasulis |title=Oscar-nominated 'Parasite' speaks to a growing divide in South Korea |url=https://news.wbfo.org/post/oscar-nominated-parasite-speaks-growing-divide-south-korea |website=news.wbfo.org |access-date=7 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207131837/https://news.wbfo.org/post/oscar-nominated-parasite-speaks-growing-divide-south-korea |archive-date=7 February 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but for the poor Kims as well.\n\nCritics have also considered the themes of [[colonialism]] and [[imperialism]]. According to Ju-Hyun Park, the film plays out within \"the capitalist economic order inaugurated and upheld in Korea by [[United States Forces Korea|colonial occupation]],\" and the use of English language in the film denotes prestige within that economic system.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://tropicsofmeta.com/2020/02/17/reading-colonialism-in-parasite/|title=Reading Colonialism in \"Parasite\"|last=Park|first=Ju-Hyun|date=17 February 2020|website=Tropics of Meta|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218055749/https://tropicsofmeta.com/2020/02/17/reading-colonialism-in-parasite/|archive-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> The Park family's son, Da-song, is obsessed with \"[[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indians]]\" and owns Native American-themed toys and inauthentic replicas.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chu |first1=Li-Wei |title=Interview: Dissecting the hidden motifs of 'Parasite' with director Bong Joon-Ho |url=https://fromtheintercom.com/interview-director-bong-joon-ho/ |website=From the Intercom |access-date=12 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212063116/https://fromtheintercom.com/interview-director-bong-joon-ho/ |archive-date=12 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cea |first1=Max |title=''Parasite'''s Wild Ending, Broken Down |url=https://www.gq.com/story/bong-joon-ho-breaks-down-parasites-wild-ending |website=GQ |access-date=12 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212200908/https://www.gq.com/story/bong-joon-ho-breaks-down-parasites-wild-ending |archive-date=12 February 2020 }}</ref> Bong has noted that \"the Native Americans have a very complicated and long, deep history. But in this family, that story is reduced to a young boy's hobby and decoration... That's what happens in our current time: The context and meaning behind these actual things only exists as a surface-level thing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/10/23/parasite-bong-joon-ho-ending-explained/|title=''Parasite'' director Bong Joon Ho discusses the film's twisty ending|last=Holub|first=Christian|date=23 October 2019|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213063431/https://ew.com/movies/2019/10/23/parasite-bong-joon-ho-ending-explained/|archive-date=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nBong has referred to ''Parasite'' as an upstairs/downstairs or \"stairway movie\",<ref name=\"JungEA\" /> in which staircases are used as a motif to represent the positions of the Kim and Park families as well as those of Moon-gwang.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rao |first=Sonia |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/10/24/unpacking-metaphorical-ending-parasite/?outputType=amp |title=Unpacking the 'metaphorical' ending of 'Parasite' |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=24 October 2019 |access-date=23 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107173908/https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/10/24/unpacking-metaphorical-ending-parasite/?outputType=amp|archive-date=7 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The semi-basement apartment that the Kims live in are common for poorer Seoul residents due to their low rent prices, despite having several issues such as mold and increased risk of disease.<ref name=\"classconflict\" /> [[East Asian Monsoon|Monsoon]] floods such as the one depicted in the film commonly damage these types of residences the most.<ref name=\"WBFO\" />\n\nAccording to Bong, the ending implies that Ki-woo will not be able to earn the funds needed to buy the house as it shows Ki-woo while still in the basement; he described this shot as a \"surefire kill\" (\ud655\uc778\uc0ac\uc0b4), referring to a [[coup de grace]] to ensure death.<ref name=JungEA /> The ending song, translating to \"546 years\" refers to Ki-woo working to make money to get the house. Its title is an allegory that is a calculation made by Bong that it will take approximately 546 years for Ki-woo to finally earn the amount of money to purchase the house; Choi Woo-shik stated that \"I'm pretty sure Ki-woo is one of those bright kids. He'll come up with some idea, and he would just go into the German family's house, and I think he will rescue his father.\"<ref name=HarrisChoiInt/> According to many interpretations, this dream ascribes to a [[bootstrapping]] mentality and is unlikely to be achieved;<ref name=\"JungEA\" /><ref name=\"Bean\" /><ref name=\"HarrisChoiInt\" /> furthermore, \"it does not address the fundamental problem at hand. Even in this fantasy scenario, Ki-taek would still be contained in the house by a legal system that would seek his prosecution and imprisonment. The forces that created and upheld the Kim family's separation would not be undone, merely adapted to.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Release ==\n[[File:Parasite (film) director and cast in 2019.jpg|thumb|Director and stars at an April 2019 press event.|293x293px]]\n[[Neon (distributor)|Neon]] acquired the North American rights to the film at the 2018 [[American Film Market]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=McNary |first1=Dave |title=Bong Joon-Ho's Drama ''Parasite'' Bought by Neon |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/bong-joon-ho-parasite-neon-1203015944/ |website=Variety |access-date=3 February 2019 |language=en |date=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203202148/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/bong-joon-ho-parasite-neon-1203015944/ |archive-date=3 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=AFM: Neon Nabs Bong Joon-ho's 'Parasite' From CJ Entertainment |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bong-joon-ho-s-parasite-picked-up-by-neon-at-afm-2018-1156727 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=3 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203202052/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bong-joon-ho-s-parasite-picked-up-by-neon-at-afm-2018-1156727 |archive-date=3 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film's rights were also pre-sold to German-speaking territories (Koch Films), French-speaking territories (The Jokers) and Japan (Bitters End).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Noh |first1=Jean |title=Bong Joon Ho thriller ''Parasite'' sells to US, Japan, France |url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/bong-joon-ho-thriller-parasite-sells-to-us-japan-france/5134106.article |website=Screen |access-date=3 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203202217/https://www.screendaily.com/news/bong-joon-ho-thriller-parasite-sells-to-us-japan-france/5134106.article |archive-date=3 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film had its world premiere at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival]] on 21 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.festival-cannes.com/en/press/press-articles/communique/articles/the-screenings-guide-2019 |title=The Screenings Guide 2019 |date=9 May 2019 |access-date=9 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509101313/https://www.festival-cannes.com/en/press/press-articles/communique/articles/the-screenings-guide-2019|archive-date=9 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released in South Korea on 30 May 2019.<ref name=\"Naver\">{{cite web |url=https://movie.naver.com/movie/bi/mi/basic.nhn?code=161967 |title=\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9 |website=[[Naver]] Movie |access-date=8 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408034341/https://movie.naver.com/movie/bi/mi/basic.nhn%3Fcode%3D161967|archive-date=8 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"release\" />\n\nIt was released in Australia and New Zealand by [[Madman Entertainment|Madman Films]] on 27 June 2019<ref>{{cite web |title=Madman Films \u2013 Posts |url=https://www.facebook.com/madmanfilms/photos/a.196868033666540/2479620522057935/?type=3&theater |publisher=[[Facebook]] |access-date=1 January 2020 |date=20 June 2019 |quote=Spread the word. Bong Joon Ho's new masterpiece, ''PARASITE'' opens in Australian cinemas June 27.}}</ref> (becoming both the highest-ever-grossing Korean film in the region<ref>{{cite web |title=Madman Films \u2013 Posts |url=https://www.facebook.com/madmanfilms/photos/a.196868033666540/2537566332930020/?type=3&theater |publisher=[[Facebook]] |access-date=1 January 2020 |quote=[...] ''Parasite'', which is now the highest grossing Korean film of all time at the Australian & New Zealand box office [...]}}</ref> and the distributor's highest-ever-grossing non-English-language film in Australia),<ref>{{cite web |title=Madman Films \u2013 Posts |url=https://www.facebook.com/madmanfilms/photos/a.196868033666540/2850457264974257/?type=3&theater |publisher=[[Facebook]] |access-date=1 January 2020 |date=23 December 2019 |quote=Bong Joon Ho's ''Parasite'' has just become Madman's most successful non-English-language film at the Australian box office of all time.}}</ref> Russia on 4 July 2019, and in the United States and Canada on 11 October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bong-joon-ho-s-palme-d-winner-parasite-get-awards-release-1214522 |title=Bong Joon Ho's Palme d'Or Winner ''Parasite'' Will Release in Time for Awards Season |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Mia |last=Galuppo |date=30 May 2019 |access-date=30 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530200626/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bong-joon-ho-s-palme-d-winner-parasite-get-awards-release-1214522|archive-date=30 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The film was originally scheduled to be screened as a closing film at FIRST International Film Festival Xining in China on 28 July 2019, but on 27 July, the film festival organizers announced that the screening was cancelled for \"technical reasons.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Rebecca |title=Bong Joon-ho's Palme d'Or Winner ''Parasite'' Pulled From China Festival |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/parasite-bong-joon-ho-first-festival-china-palme-dor-1203282678/ |date=28 July 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=30 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730143510/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/parasite-bong-joon-ho-first-festival-china-palme-dor-1203282678/ |archive-date=30 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIt was licensed for the United Kingdom and Ireland by [[Curzon Artificial Eye]] at Cannes, and had preview screenings with an interview with Bong Joon-ho shared live by satellite on 3 February 2020, followed by the film's general release on 7 February.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Parasite'' Tickets & Showtimes |url=https://www.curzoncinemas.com/film-info/parasite-bong-joon-ho |publisher=[[Curzon Cinemas]] |access-date=1 January 2020 |quote=Director Bong Joon-ho joins us live in person for a preview Q&A at Curzon Mayfair that will be shared via satellite. [...] Wednesday 3 February 6.00pm [...] UK Release Date 7 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101073142/https://www.curzoncinemas.com/film-info/parasite-bong-joon-ho |archive-date=1 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Neon expanded the number of North American theaters showing the film from 1,060 to 2,001 starting the weekend of 14 February 2020, following the film's recognition at the Academy Awards,<ref name = NUM2>{{cite web|url = https://www.the-numbers.com/box-office-chart/weekend/2020/02/14|title = Weekend Domestic Chart for February 14, 2020|accessdate = 20 February 2020|website = The Numbers|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200218010457/https://www.the-numbers.com/box-office-chart/weekend/2020/02/14|archive-date = 18 February 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> despite the film having already been released on home video in the region.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2020/film/news/parasite-release-theaters-oscars-neon-1203499975/ | title = 'Parasite' Doubles North American Release After Historic Oscar Wins | first = Dave | last = McNary | date = 10 February 2020 | access-date = 10 February 2020 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200211025249/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/parasite-release-theaters-oscars-neon-1203499975/ | archive-date = 11 February 2020 | url-status = live }}</ref> A special [[IMAX]] remaster was shown at limited North American theaters during the week of 21 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2020/film/news/parasite-imax-remaster-release-1203509462/ | title = 'Parasite' to Get Digitally Re-Mastered Imax Release for One Week | first = Dave | last = McNary | date = 20 February 2020 | accessdate = 20 February 2020 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200220201432/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/parasite-imax-remaster-release-1203509462/ | archive-date = 20 February 2020 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n=== Home media ===\nOn 28 January 2020, ''Parasite'' was released on [[Blu-ray]] in [[Blu-ray#Region codes|Region A]] and [[DVD]] in [[DVD region code|Region 1]] by [[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Parasite-Blu-ray-Kang-Ho-Song/dp/B07YTDYDYB/|title=Parasite [Blu-ray]|website=[[Amazon.com]]|access-date=13 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113061307/https://www.amazon.com/Parasite-Blu-ray-Kang-Ho-Song/dp/B07YTDYDYB|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Parasite-Kang-Ho-Song/dp/B081WQQSYS/|title=Parasite [DVD]|website=[[Amazon.com]]|access-date=13 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211102353/https://www.amazon.com/Parasite-Kang-Ho-Song/dp/B081WQQSYS|archive-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 13 February 2020, it was announced that the film will be released on home media by [[the Criterion Collection]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/parasite-join-criterion-collection-1279250|title=Oscar Winner 'Parasite' to Join Criterion Collection|last=Galuppo|first=Mia|date=13 February 2020|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=13 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213201609/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/parasite-join-criterion-collection-1279250|archive-date=13 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3604763/bong-joon-hos-parasite-memories-murder-joining-criterion-collection/|title=Bong Joon Ho's 'Parasite' and 'Memories of Murder' Both Joining the Criterion Collection|last=Squires|first=John|date=13 February 2020|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|access-date=13 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213201605/https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3604763/bong-joon-hos-parasite-memories-murder-joining-criterion-collection/|archive-date=13 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 February 2020, the subscription-based [[Streaming services|streaming service]] [[Hulu]] announced that it had secured exclusive rights to stream the film in the United States, starting on 8 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/24/21150977/parasite-movie-streaming-hulu-april-oscars-neon-bong-joon-ho|title=Best Picture winner Parasite will stream exclusively on Hulu beginning April 8th|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=2020-02-24|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225133837/https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/24/21150977/parasite-movie-streaming-hulu-april-oscars-neon-bong-joon-ho|archive-date=25 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, [[Amazon Prime|Amazon Prime Video]] began streaming the film on 28 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gqindia.com/entertainment/content/oscar-winning-movie-parasite-stream-amazon-prime-video|title=Oscar-winning film Parasite is finally releasing on this OTT platform and here's how you can watch it|work=[[GQ (Indian edition)|GQ India]]|last=Shah|first=Vrutika|date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331071659/https://www.gqindia.com/entertainment/content/oscar-winning-movie-parasite-stream-amazon-prime-video|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2020|3|15}}, ''Parasite'' has grossed $53.48 million in the United States and Canada, and $213.5 million in other territories (including $71.19 million from South Korea), for a worldwide total of $266.9 million.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |title=''Parasite'' (2019) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]]|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt6751668/ |access-date= 20 March 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191204002650/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt6751668/ |archive-date= 4 December 2019 |url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=NUM>{{cite web |title=''Parasite'' (2019)|website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/gi-saeng-chung-(South-Korea)-(2019)#tab=summary |access-date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204002650/https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/gi-saeng-chung-(South-Korea)-(2019)#tab=summary |archive-date=4 December 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> It set a new record for Bong, becoming the first of his films to gross over $100 million worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/parasite-sets-new-record-for-director-bong-joon-ho-at-indie-box-office/ |title='Parasite' Sets New Record for Director Bong Joon-Ho at Indie Box Office |date=3 November 2019 |website=TheWrap |language=en-US|access-date=4 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104063450/https://www.thewrap.com/parasite-sets-new-record-for-director-bong-joon-ho-at-indie-box-office/|archive-date=4 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the film's United States opening weekend, the film grossed $376,264 from three theatres. Its per-venue average of $125,421 was the best since ''[[La La Land (film)|La La Land]]''{{'}}s in 2016, and the best ever for an international film.<ref name=USdebut>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/gemini-man-will-smith-joker-addams-family-jexi-weekend-box-office-1202757855/ |title=''Joker'' $55M+ Scores 2nd Weekend October Record, ''Addams Family'' Rich $30M+, ''Gemini Man'' Still Not Dazzling $20M \u2013 Sunday B.O. Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=13 October 2019 |access-date=13 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191011150127/https://deadline.com/2019/10/gemini-man-will-smith-joker-addams-family-jexi-weekend-box-office-1202757855/ |archive-date=11 October 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> It expanded to 33 theatres in its second weekend, making $1.24 million,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/maleficent-mistress-of-evil-zombieland-double-tap-weekend-box-office-1202763525/ |title='Maleficent: Mistress Of Evil' No Magic With $36M+, 'Joker' Still Stealing 2nd Place From 'Zombieland 2' With $28M+ |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=20 October 2019 |access-date=20 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019220728/https://deadline.com/2019/10/maleficent-mistress-of-evil-zombieland-double-tap-weekend-box-office-1202763525/ |archive-date=19 October 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> and then made $1.8 million from 129 theatres in its third.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/synonyms-nadav-lapid-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-frankie-ira-sachs-isabelle-huppert-specialty-box-office-1202769933/ |title='Synonyms' And Kanye West's 'Jesus Is King' Have Solid Premieres, 'Frankie' Debuts Soft \u2013 Specialty Box Office |last=Ramos |first=Dino-Ray |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=27 October 2019 |access-date=27 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191027175507/https://deadline.com/2019/10/synonyms-nadav-lapid-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-frankie-ira-sachs-isabelle-huppert-specialty-box-office-1202769933/ |archive-date=27 October 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film made $2.5 million in its fourth weekend and $2.6 million in its fifth.<ref>{{cite web |last=Brueggemann |first=Tom |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/box-office-amazon-honey-boy-netflix-marriage-story-1202188521/ |title=Amazon's 'Honey Boy' Tops Netflix's 'Marriage Story' In Select Theaters |website=[[IndieWire]] |date=10 November 2019 |access-date=10 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110194039/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/box-office-amazon-honey-boy-netflix-marriage-story-1202188521/ |archive-date=10 November 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film's initial theatre count peaked in its sixth weekend at 620, when it made $1.9 million.<ref>{{cite web |last=Brueggemann |first=Tom |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/waves-a24-box-office-arthouse-1202190157/ |title='Waves' Makes Box Office Splash as Amazon and Netflix Stay Quiet |website=[[IndieWire]] |date=17 November 2019 |access-date=17 November 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117190609/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/waves-a24-box-office-arthouse-1202190157/ |archive-date=17 November 2019}}</ref> It continued to hold well in the following weekends, making $1.3 million and $1 million.<ref>{{cite web |last=Brueggemann |first=Tom |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/box-office-dark-waters-arthouse-openers-1202191841/ |title='Dark Waters' Leads Tepid Arthouse Openers at Crowded Box Office |website=[[IndieWire]] |date=24 November 2019 |access-date=24 November 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125113120/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/box-office-dark-waters-arthouse-openers-1202191841/ |archive-date=25 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Brueggemann |first=Tom |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/holiday-box-office-harriet-jojo-rabbit-two-popes-1202193331/ |title='Harriet,' 'Jojo Rabbit,' and 'Parasite' Reap Holiday Box Office Bounty |website=[[IndieWire]] |date=1 December 2019 |url-status= live |access-date=1 December 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191201182642/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/holiday-box-office-harriet-jojo-rabbit-two-popes-1202193331/ |archive-date= 1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn its tenth week of release the film crossed the $20 million mark (rare for an international film), making $632,500 from 306 theatres.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/uncut-gems-shines-with-biggest-a24-per-screen-opening-a-hidden-life-debuts-lionsgate-drops-limited-bombshell-release-specialty-box-office-1202809673/ |title=Uncut Gems' Shines With Biggest A24 Per-Screen Opening, 'A Hidden Life' Debuts, Lionsgate Drops Limited 'Bombshell' Release \u2013 Specialty Box Office |last=Ramos |first=Dino-Ray |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=15 December 2019 |access-date=15 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215173332/https://deadline.com/2019/12/uncut-gems-shines-with-biggest-a24-per-screen-opening-a-hidden-life-debuts-lionsgate-drops-limited-bombshell-release-specialty-box-office-1202809673/ |archive-date=15 December 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> During the weekend of the Oscars, the film made $1.5 million from 1,060 theaters for a running total of $35.5 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/birds-of-prey-weekend-box-office-margot-robbie-1202853768/ |title=How 'Birds Of Prey' Went Astray With $33M+ Opening |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=9 February 2020 |access-date=9 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208173530/https://deadline.com/2020/02/birds-of-prey-weekend-box-office-margot-robbie-1202853768/|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After Neon's doubling of theater showings in the week following the Academy Awards, the film made $5.5 million in North American revenue, making it one of the biggest Best Picture bumps since ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' in 2009 and the biggest in ten years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/sonic-the-hedgehog-birds-of-prey-will-ferrell-downhill-valentines-day-box-office-1202860119/ |title='Sonic The Hedgehog' Rings Up Record Domestic Videogame Pic Debut Of $57M & 4-Day $68M; Global Launch At $100M |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=16 February 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=16 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215000134/https://deadline.com/2020/02/sonic-the-hedgehog-birds-of-prey-will-ferrell-downhill-valentines-day-box-office-1202860119/ |archive-date=15 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn its native South Korea, ''Parasite'' grossed US$20.7 million on its opening weekend,<ref name=\"NUM\"/> and would close its box office run with US$72.2 million and more than 10 million admissions, roughly one-fifth of the country's population and ranking among the year's top five films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/reports.jsp?blbdComCd=601008&seq=569&mode=VIEW |title=Korean Theaters Sell 227 Million Tickets in Record Year|date=January 3, 2020|publisher=Korean Film Council|author=Pierce Conran}}</ref><ref>[http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/02/398_284031.html \"Parasite\" to give much-needed boost to Korean cinema] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226193202/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/02/398_284031.html |date=26 February 2020 }}, The Korea Times</ref>  On 5 February, ''Parasite'' became the first Korean film in nearly 15 years that surpassed one million moviegoers in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.kbs.co.kr/news/view.do?ncd=4376313 |title=\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9, 15\ub144 \ub9cc\uc5d0 \u65e5 '100\ub9cc \uad00\uac1d' \ub3cc\ud30c...'\uc698\uc0ac\ub9c8' \uc774\ud6c4 \ucc98\uc74c |website=KBS \ub274\uc2a4 |language=ko|access-date=7 February 2020}}</ref> In the UK, it broke the record for the opening weekend of a non-English-language film, making \u00a31.4 million ($1.8 million) including previews over its debut weekend, from 135 screens,<ref name=\"DeadlineUK\">{{cite news|title='Parasite' To Expand Significantly In UK After Record-Breaking Opening Weekend|work=Deadline Hollywood|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/parasite-record-breaking-uk-box-office-debut-1202856229/|date=10 February 2020|access-date=12 February 2020|last=Grater|first=Tom|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211181658/https://deadline.com/2020/02/parasite-record-breaking-uk-box-office-debut-1202856229/|archive-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and in Australia it took in over $1.9 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/curzon-madman-cineart-film-development-fund-1202859067/|title=UK's Curzon, Australia's Madman, Benelux's Cineart Partner To Launch $1.6M Film Development Fund|last=Grater|first=Tom|last2=Grater|first2=Tom|date=13 February 2020|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=14 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215022744/https://deadline.com/2020/02/curzon-madman-cineart-film-development-fund-1202859067/|archive-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the weekend following its Oscars wins, the film made $12.8 million from 43 countries, bringing its international total to $161 million, and its global running gross over the $200 million mark.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tartaglione |first1=Nancy |title='Sonic The Hedgehog' Races To $43M Overseas For $100M Global Bow; 'Birds Of Prey' Flaps To $143M WW \u2013 International Box Office |url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/sonic-the-hedgehog-opening-birds-of-prey-global-international-box-office-1202860971/ |accessdate=18 February 2020 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=16 February 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217122710/https://deadline.com/2020/02/sonic-the-hedgehog-opening-birds-of-prey-global-international-box-office-1202860971/ |archive-date=17 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFollowing its Academy Awards success, ''Parasite'' received significant rescreening for both domestic and international audiences, generating significant further revenue. The Associated Press reported the biggest \"Oscar effect\" since 2001 after ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'' won the Oscar for Best Picture. ''Parasite''{{'}}s box office revenue increased by more than 230% compared to the prior week, grossing $2.15 million in a single day. It also ranked No. 1 in Japan, the first Korean film to do so in 15 years.<ref>Parasite takes second bite at local box office https://www.smh.com.au/culture/movies/parasite-takes-second-bite-at-local-box-office-20200218-p541so.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224015746/https://www.smh.com.au/culture/movies/parasite-takes-second-bite-at-local-box-office-20200218-p541so.html |date=24 February 2020 }}</ref> [[Motion Picture Association of America|The Motion Picture Distributors Association]] of Australia announced that $749K worth of cinema tickets were sold in a single weekend, with the film re-entering the top 10 at the local box office more than six months after it debuted in Australian cinemas. ''Parasite'' also surged back to fourth place in South Korea's box office by attracting more than 80,000 viewers.<ref>Oscar-winning Parasite grosses $2.15 mn a day in N. America, ranks No. 1 in Japan \nhttps://pulsenews.co.kr/view.php?sc=30800028&year=2020&no=167522&_ga=2.245558797.80415101.1582162023-140936798.1581898892</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donga.com/en/east/article/all/20200218/1982094/1/Revenue-of-Parasite-increases-by-234-in-North-America|title=Revenue of \u2018Parasite\u2019 increases by 234% in North America|work=Dong-A Ilbo|date=February 18, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224015958/http://www.donga.com/en/east/article/all/20200218/1982094/1/Revenue-of-Parasite-increases-by-234-in-North-America|archive-date=24 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 99% based on 426 reviews, with an average rating of 9.37/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"An urgent, brilliantly layered look at timely social themes, ''Parasite'' finds writer-director Bong Joon Ho in near-total command of his craft.\"<ref name=\"tomatoes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/parasite_2019|title=''Parasite'' (''Gisaengchung'') (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211232005/https://rottentomatoes.com/m/parasite_2019|archive-date=11 December 2019|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], it has a weighted average score of 96 out of 100, based on 52 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |title=''Parasite'' Reviews |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/parasite |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |access-date=19 October 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191018183825/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/parasite |archive-date= 18 October 2019 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[A. O. Scott]] described the film as \"wildly entertaining, the kind of smart, generous, aesthetically energized movie that obliterates the tired distinctions between art films and popcorn movies.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Scott |first=A. O. |author-link=A. O. Scott|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/04/movies/new-york-film-festival.html |title=Old Masters and Fresh Surprises at the New York Film Festival |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |access-date=7 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191007030522/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/04/movies/new-york-film-festival.html |archive-date=7 October 2019 |url-status=live|date=4 October 2019}}</ref> Bilge Ebiri of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine wrote that ''Parasite'' is \"a work that is itself in a state of constant, agitated transformation\u2014a nerve-racking masterpiece whose spell lingers long after its haunting final image.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Bilge Ebiri |title=Bong Joon-ho's ''Parasite'' Is a Nerve-Racking Masterpiece |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/05/bong-joon-hos-parasite-is-a-nerve-racking-masterpiece.html |website=[[New York Magazine]] |access-date=7 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191007104809/https://www.vulture.com/2019/05/bong-joon-hos-parasite-is-a-nerve-racking-masterpiece.html |archive-date=7 October 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In his five-star review of the film, Dave Calhoun of ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' praised the social commentary and stated that \"This is a dazzling work, surprising and fully gripping from beginning to end, full of big bangs and small wonders.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Dave Calhoun |url=https://www.timeout.com/us/film/parasite |title=''Parasite'' |website=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] |publisher=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] |access-date=7 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191007190446/https://www.timeout.com/us/film/parasite |archive-date=7 October 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s Jessica Kiang described the film as \"a wild, wild ride,\" writing that \"Bong is back and on brilliant form, but he is unmistakably, roaringly furious, and it registers because the target is so deserving, so enormous, so 2019: ''Parasite'' is a tick fat with the bitter blood of class rage.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Jessica Kiang |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/parasite-review-1203221435/ |title=Film Review: ''Parasite'' |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=7 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713080323/https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/parasite-review-1203221435/ |archive-date=13 July 2019 |url-status=live|date=21 May 2019 }}</ref> ''[[The A. V. Club]]''{{'}}s A. A. Dowd awarded the film an A\u2212 grade, praising the fun and surprising twists.<ref name=\"avc\">{{cite web |url=https://film.avclub.com/parasite-may-be-bong-joon-ho-s-most-thrilling-ride-on-t-1838933205 |title=''Parasite'' May be Bong Joon Ho's Most Thrilling Ride on the Genre-Hopping Snowpiercer Express |last=Dowd |first=A. A. |date=10 October 2019 |access-date=10 October 2019 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191011084422/https://film.avclub.com/parasite-may-be-bong-joon-ho-s-most-thrilling-ride-on-t-1838933205 |archive-date=11 October 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Joshua Rivera from ''[[GQ]]'' gave a glowing review and declared ''Parasite'' to be \"Maybe 2019's best film\", further adding, \"It's so top-to-bottom satisfying that even being completely spoiled couldn't ruin it \u2013 but if you can come to it cold, you'll be floored.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gq.com/story/parasite-review |title=10 Reasons Why Parasite May Be 2019's Best Film |last=Rivera |first=Joshua |date=11 October 2019 |work=GQ |access-date=18 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218064844/https://www.gq.com/story/parasite-review |archive-date=18 December 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMichael Wood writing for the ''[[London Review of Books]]'' found the film to follow a theme of class consciousness to be consistent with the director's previous film ''Snowpiercer'' stating, \"The theme of social ascent, or social difference as a landscape, could hardly be more obvious, but we are beginning to get the movie's idea: not to avoid stereotypes but to keep crashing into them\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/the-paper/v42/n03/michael-wood/at-the-movies|title=Michael Wood \u00b7 At the Movies: \u2018Parasite\u2019 \u00b7 LRB 27 January 2020|first=Michael|last=Wood|date=27 January 2020|website=London Review of Books|accessdate=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226230249/https://lrb.co.uk/the-paper/v42/n03/michael-wood/at-the-movies|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Paddy Kehoe writing for [[RT\u00c9]] found the film to be insufficient as a social commentary by not presenting alternative viewpoints giving the film 2.5/5 stars and stating: \"No doubt Asian capitalist interests are well-served in the end, there won't be rioting in the streets on the back of this one. A film is hardly effective satire if it doesn't point up a route to radical change\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kehoe |first1=Paddy |title=Parasite: worth seeing if only for after-screen debate |url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/movie-reviews/2020/0113/1106123-masquerading-as-sharp-satire-parasite-is-limp-escapism/ |website=[[RT\u00c9]] |accessdate=23 February 2020 |language=en |date=6 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215140808/https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/movie-reviews/2020/0113/1106123-masquerading-as-sharp-satire-parasite-is-limp-escapism/ |archive-date=15 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> UK film website TheShiznit gave the film an A, noting \"it makes you wonder what the inflection point for such behaviour is in a culture where manners and servitude are drilled into those who can't afford not to have them\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theshiznit.co.uk/review/review-parasite-delves-into-the-darkest-recesses-of-humanity.php|title=Review: Parasite delves into the darkest recesses of humanity &#124; Movie Review|website=TheShiznit.co.uk|accessdate=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228210905/http://www.theshiznit.co.uk/review/review-parasite-delves-into-the-darkest-recesses-of-humanity.php|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Parasite'' ranked 1st in a survey conducted by IndieWire of over 300 critics, in the Best Film, Best Director, Best Screenplay and Best Foreign Film categories.<ref name=\"auto8\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/best-movies-2019-critics-survey-poll-performances-parasite-adam-driver-lupita-nyongo-1202197615/ |title=2019 Critics Poll: The Best Films and Performances According to Over 300 Critics From Around the World |date=16 December 2019|access-date=17 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191216162724/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/best-movies-2019-critics-survey-poll-performances-parasite-adam-driver-lupita-nyongo-1202197615/|archive-date=16 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Parasite'' appeared on over 240 critics' year-end top-ten lists, including 77 who ranked the film first.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-top-10-best-movies-of-2019 |title=Best of 2019: Film Critic Top Ten Lists |website=Metacritic|access-date=6 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112201058/https://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-top-10-best-movies-of-2019|archive-date=12 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], ''Parasite'' was rated as the best film of 2019<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-movies-released-in-2019 |title=The Best Movies of 2019 |website=Metacritic|access-date=9 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108120521/https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-movies-released-in-2019|archive-date=8 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and ranked 7th among the films with the highest scores of the decade.<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-movies-of-the-decade-2010s |title=Best Movies of the Decade (2010\u201319) |website=Metacritic|access-date=9 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101162640/https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-movies-of-the-decade-2010s|archive-date=1 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> {{As of|2019|12|28}}, it is the 40th highest-rated film of all time on the website.<ref>{{cite web |title=Best Movies of All Time |url=https://www.metacritic.com/browse/movies/score/metascore/all/filtered?sort=desc |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=28 December 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190809210855/https://www.metacritic.com/browse/movies/score/metascore/all/filtered?sort=desc |archive-date= 9 August 2019 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Parasite}}\n[[File:Bong Joon-ho 2017.jpg|thumb|upright=0.68|[[Bong Joon-ho]] garnered widespread critical acclaim for his direction and was awarded the [[Academy Award for Best Director]] in 2020.]]\n\n''Parasite'' won the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival]]. It became the first South Korean film to do so, as well as the first film to win with a unanimous vote since ''[[Blue Is the Warmest Colour]]'' at the [[2013 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Mumford\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/live/2019/may/25/cannes-film-festival-2019-palme-dor-winner-announced-live |title=Cannes 2019: Bong Joon-ho's Parasite wins the Palme d'Or \u2013 as it happened |first=Gwilym |last=Mumford |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=25 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526093153/https://www.theguardian.com/film/live/2019/may/25/cannes-film-festival-2019-palme-dor-winner-announced-live |archivedate=26 May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"D'Alessandro\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/parasite-bong-joon-ho-north-korea-jokes-cannes-palme-dor-1202622402/ |title='Parasite' Palme d'Or Winner Bong Joon-Ho On Pic's North Korea Jokes \u2013 Cannes |first1=Anthony |last1=D'Alessandro |date=25 May 2019 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=26 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526020408/https://deadline.com/2019/05/parasite-bong-joon-ho-north-korea-jokes-cannes-palme-dor-1202622402/ |archivedate=26 May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[77th Golden Globe Awards]], the film was nominated for three awards, including [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]], and won [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]], becoming the first ever South Korean film to achieve that feat.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/2020-golden-globes-nominations-list-nominees-1203426905/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209155146/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/2020-golden-globes-nominations-list-nominees-1203426905/ |title=Golden Globes 2020: The Complete Nominations List |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=9 December 2019 |accessdate=9 December 2019 |archivedate=9 December 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/10/785090210/parasite-director-bong-joon-ho-wanted-to-reflect-the-truth-of-current-times |title='Parasite' Director Bong Joon-ho 'Wanted To Reflect The Truth Of Current Times' |last=Ulaby |first=Neda |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=10 December 2019 |accessdate=12 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191212221503/https://www.npr.org/2019/12/10/785090210/parasite-director-bong-joon-ho-wanted-to-reflect-the-truth-of-current-times |archivedate=12 December 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIt became the second international film to ever be nominated for the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]] since ''[[Life Is Beautiful]]'' (1997), and ultimately won the category, making it the first international film to win the prize.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/23a16f9d37b9bab3050acda880045c76|title='Parasite' wins at SAG Awards, so do Pitt and Aniston|date=19 January 2020|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=14 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214013840/https://apnews.com/23a16f9d37b9bab3050acda880045c76|archive-date=14 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/entertainment/2020/1/20/Parasite-Screen-Actors-Guild-best-ensemble-award.html|title='Parasite' opens important door for foreign-language films with SAG win|publisher=[[CNN]]|language=en|accessdate=14 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214051258/https://www.cnnphilippines.com/entertainment/2020/1/20/Parasite-Screen-Actors-Guild-best-ensemble-award.html|archive-date=14 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Parasite'' was also nominated for four awards at the [[73rd British Academy Film Awards]]\u2014[[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Director]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], and [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language|Best Film Not in the English Language]]. It became the first South Korean film to receive nominations at the [[British Academy Film Awards]] (except for Best Film Not in the English Language), and went on to win Best Original Screenplay and Best Film Not in the English Language.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/02/bafta-winners-2020-1202208012/|title=BAFTA Awards: '1917' Crowned Best Film (Full Winners List)|last=Lattanzio|first=Ryan|date=2 February 2020|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202193402/https://www.indiewire.com/2020/02/bafta-winners-2020-1202208012/|archivedate=2 February 2020|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=001&aid=0011373001|title='\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9', \uc601\uad6d \uc544\uce74\ub370\ubbf8 \uc678\uad6d\uc5b4\uc601\ud654\uc0c1\u00b7\uc624\ub9ac\uc9c0\ub110 \uac01\ubcf8\uc0c1 2\uad00\uc655|trans-title='The Parasite', British Academy Foreign Language Film Awards, Original Screenplay 2nd Prize|work=[[Yonhap News Agency]]|language=ko|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200313223207/https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=001&aid=0011373001|archive-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live|accessdate=3 February 2020|via=[[Naver]]}}</ref>\n\n''Parasite'' was submitted as the [[List of South Korean submissions for the Academy Award for Best International Feature Film|South Korean entry]] for [[Academy Award for Best International Feature Film|Best International Feature Film]] for the [[92nd Academy Awards]], making the December shortlist.<ref name=\"South Korea\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kofic.or.kr/kofic/business/board/selectBoardDetail.do?boardNumber=4&boardSeqNumber=49491 |title=\uc81c92\ud68c \uc544\uce74\ub370\ubbf8\uc601\ud654\uc0c1 \uad6d\uc81c\uc7a5\ud3b8\uc601\ud654 \ubd80\ubb38 \ud55c\uad6d\uc601\ud654 \ucd9c\ud488\uc791 \uc120\uc815\uacb0\uacfc (Selected Results of Korean Films for International Feature Films at the 92nd Academy Film Awards) |last=Kim |first=Hye-Ju |publisher=[[Korean Film Council]] |date=21 August 2019 |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/oscars-korea-selects-palme-dor-winner-parasite-international-feature-film-award-1203309121/ |title=Oscars: South Korea Selects Palme d'Or Winner 'Parasite' for International Feature Film Award |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=21 August 2019 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821173038/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/oscars-korea-selects-palme-dor-winner-parasite-international-feature-film-award-1203309121/ |archivedate=21 August 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2019/12/16/us/ap-us-oscars-international-film-shortlist.html |title=10 Films Make Shortlist for Oscars' Best International Film |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=17 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217134423/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2019/12/16/us/ap-us-oscars-international-film-shortlist.html |archivedate=17 December 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> It went on to win four awards\u2014[[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], and Best International Feature Film. ''Parasite'' became the first non-English language film in [[Academy Awards]] [[List of Academy Award records|history]] to win Best Picture. ''Parasite'' also became the first South Korean film to be nominated for Best Picture at the Academy Awards and the second East Asian film to receive a nomination for Best Picture since ''[[Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon]]'' (2000),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200113000836|title='Parasite' earns six Oscar nominations, including best picture|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=13 January 2020|work=[[The Korea Herald]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115032343/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200113000836|archivedate=15 January 2020|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref>, and Bong Joon-ho became the fourth Asian to receive an Academy Award nomination for Best Director, becoming the second to win following [[Ang Lee]]. It also received nominations for [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]] and [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2020-01-13/parasite-oscar-nominations-everything-you-need-to-know|title=Everything you need to know about 'Parasite' and its Oscar nominations|date=13 January 2020|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115033844/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2020-01-13/parasite-oscar-nominations-everything-you-need-to-know|archivedate=15 January 2020|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200114/99210731/1|title=\ud55c\uad6d \uc601\ud654 \uccab \uc544\uce74\ub370\ubbf8\uc0c1 \ubcf4\uc778\ub2e4... \uae30\uc0dd\ucda9, 6\uac1c\ubd80\ubb38 \ub178\ubbf8\ub124\uc774\ud2b8|last=Lee|first=Seo-hyun|date=14 January 2020|work=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]]|accessdate=14 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114232449/http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200114/99210731/1|archive-date=14 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/02/in-the-absence-documentary-korean-oscar-nominee-interview-sewol.html|title=The Filmmakers Behind ''In the Absence'' on What It Can Teach Americans|author=Violet Kim|date=4 February 2020|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206005230/https://slate.com/culture/2020/02/in-the-absence-documentary-korean-oscar-nominee-interview-sewol.html|archivedate=6 February 2020|accessdate=9 February 2020}}</ref> The film is also the second film to win both the Academy Award for Best Picture and the Palme d'Or at Cannes under the latter's name in 65 years since ''[[Marty (film)|Marty]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldderby.com/article/2020/parasite-palme-dor-winner-best-picture-oscar/|title=Can \u2018Parasite\u2019 become first Palme d\u2019Or winner to claim Best Picture Oscar since \u2018Marty\u2019 did it 64 years ago?|first1=Charles|last1=Bright|first2=Charles|last2=Bright|date=16 January 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328161439/https://www.goldderby.com/article/2020/parasite-palme-dor-winner-best-picture-oscar/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> being the third film to win both grand prizes after the former and ''[[The Lost Weekend (film)|The Lost Weekend]]''.\n\nDuring Bong Joon-ho's acceptance speech at the Oscars, he paused to thank [[Martin Scorsese]], a co-nominated director, whom Bong recognized as having historical importance to the history of filmmaking which resulted in spontaneous applause from the audience in recognition of Scorsese during his speech. The following day Scorsese sent the director a personal congratulatory letter which Bong reported while on a speaking engagement at the [[Lincoln Center]] Film Society where Bong stated that he could not share the full letter from Scorsese due to its personal nature. He did, however, share the conclusion of the letter by stating that Scorsese told him that \"You've done well. Now rest. But don't rest for too long.\" Bong then added that Scorsese ended his letter by stating \"how he and other directors were waiting for my (Bong's) next movie.\"<ref>\"Everything We Know about Martin Scorsese's Killers of the Flower Moon So Far\". Paste magazine. Feb 27, 2020. [https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2020/02/martin-scorsese-killers-of-the-flower-moon-everyth.html#plot] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227155546/https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2020/02/martin-scorsese-killers-of-the-flower-moon-everyth.html#plot |date=27 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Associated Press]] commented that although the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] (AMPAS) had previously failed to adequately recognize women filmmakers in the Academy Award nominations, this time it acknowledged diversity. The AP noted that the film's victory, because of its being an Oscar-winning foreign film in a regular Academy category, opens the door for Hollywood to undergo a radical change and a different kind of advancement. ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' also stated that the film seemed to promise a \"more inclusive Oscars\" demanded by those who have previously criticized AMPAS.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mk.co.kr/news/culture/view/2020/02/137098/|title=\"\uacbd\uc7c1\uc791\ub4e4\uc5d0 \ube44\ud574 \ub108\ubb34 \uac15\ub825\", \"1\uc778\uce58 \uc815\ub3c4 \ub418\ub294 \uc790\ub9c9\uc758 \uc7a5\ubcbd' \ub6f0\uc5b4\ub118\uc5c8\ub2e4\"|publisher=[[Maeil Business Newspaper]]|language=Korean|access-date=24 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224020123/https://www.mk.co.kr/news/culture/view/2020/02/137098/|archive-date=24 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Parasite'' was nominated for Most Valuable Film of 2020 by [[Cinema for Peace]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.org/nominations-2020|title=Cinema for Peace Gala Nominations 2020|website=cinemaforpeace-foundation.org|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227140413/https://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.org/nominations-2020|archivedate=27 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n=== Spin-off television series ===\nAn [[HBO]] limited series based on the film, with Bong and [[Adam McKay]] as executive producers, is in early development.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kit |first=Borys |last2=Goldberg |first2=Lesley |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/adam-mckay-bong-joon-ho-teaming-parasite-limited-series-hbo-1268397 |title='Parasite' HBO Limited Series in the Works From Bong Joon Ho, Adam McKay |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=9 January 2020 |access-date=9 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110022107/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/adam-mckay-bong-joon-ho-teaming-parasite-limited-series-hbo-1268397 |archive-date=10 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Bong has stated that the series, also titled ''Parasite'', will explore stories \"that happen in between the sequences in the film\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Ford |first=Rebessa |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/adam-mckay-bong-joon-ho-teaming-parasite-limited-series-hbo-1268397 |title=Bong Joon Ho Says 'Parasite' Series Will Explore Stories \"That Happen in Between the Sequences in the Film\" |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=21 January 2020 |access-date=21 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110022107/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/adam-mckay-bong-joon-ho-teaming-parasite-limited-series-hbo-1268397 |archive-date=10 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/01/parasite-tv-series-bong-joon-ho-six-hour-movie-1202205540/ |title=Bong Joon Ho Reveals Epic Plans for 'Parasite' Series as a Six-Hour Movie |first1=Ryan |last1=Lattanzio |first2=Ryan |last2=Lattanzio |date=23 January 2020 |access-date=24 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124175554/https://www.indiewire.com/2020/01/parasite-tv-series-bong-joon-ho-six-hour-movie-1202205540/ |archive-date=24 January 2020 }}</ref> In February, [[Mark Ruffalo]] and [[Tilda Swinton]] were rumoured to star in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/parasite-hbo-series-cast-mark-ruffalo/|title=Exclusive: Mark Ruffalo Eyed to Star in 'Parasite' Series on HBO|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|date=10 February 2020|access-date=10 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211105309/https://collider.com/parasite-hbo-series-cast-mark-ruffalo/|archive-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/1916971|title='\ud5d0\ud06c' \ub9c8\ud06c \ub7ec\ud314\ub85c\u2192'\uc625\uc790' \ud2f8\ub2e4 \uc2a4\uc708\ud2bc...\ub4dc\ub77c\ub9c8 '\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9' \ub9c9\uac15 \ub77c\uc778\uc5c5 \ud654\uc81c|publisher=[[Korea Economic Daily]]|language=Korean|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217003544/http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/1916971|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Plans for tourist set ===\nA South Korean local government ([[Goyang City]]) plans to restore the Goyang Aqua Special Shooting Studio set, where the film ''Parasite'' was produced, and use it as a ''Parasite'' movie experience tourism facility. In addition, Goyang City has announced&nbsp;that it will invest $150 million in the&nbsp;development of&nbsp;the Goyang Film Culture Complex by 2026 to accommodate film experience [[tourism]] facilities, additional indoor studios, outdoor set production facilities, inter-Korean video content centres, and image research and development companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mk.co.kr/news/culture/view/2020/02/146969|title=`\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9` \ud604\uc7a5\uc744 \uadf8\ub300\ub85c...\uc138\ud2b8 \ubcf5\uc6d0\ud574 \uad00\uad11\ud55c\ub958 \uae30\uc9c0\ub85c|publisher=[[Maeil Business Newspaper]]|language=Korean|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213170813/https://www.mk.co.kr/news/culture/view/2020/02/146969/|archive-date=13 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tournews21.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=41207|title=\uace0\uc591\uc2dc, '\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9' \ucd2c\uc601\uc9c0 '\uace0\uc591\uc544\ucfe0\uc544\ud2b9\uc218\ucd2c\uc6a9\uc2a4\ud29c\ub514\uc624' \uccb4\ud5d8\uad00\uad11\uc2dc\uc124\ub85c \uc870\uc131!|publisher=Tournews21|language=Korean}}</ref><ref>\uc9c0\uc790\uccb4 \u3008\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9\u3009 \uad00\uad11\ucf54\uc2a4 \uac1c\ubc1c\uc774 \ubd80\ub978 \"\uac00\ub09c \ud3ec\ub974\ub178\" \ub17c\ub780 : \nhttp://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/928295.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217004527/http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/928295.html |date=17 February 2020 }}</ref> However, criticisms have been raised about the commercialization of areas known for poverty in South Korea as tourist destinations without concrete steps being taken to address the issues at hand.<ref>'\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9' \uad00\uad11 \ub9c8\ucf00\ud305...\ube48\uace4 \ud3ec\ub974\ub178, \ube48\uace4 \ub3d9\ubb3c\uc6d0\uc778\uac00  https://www.sisaweekly.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=30764</ref><ref>\uc9c0\uc790\uccb4 \u3008\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9\u3009 \uad00\uad11\ucf54\uc2a4 \uac1c\ubc1c\uc774 \ubd80\ub978 \"\uac00\ub09c \ud3ec\ub974\ub178\" \ub17c\ub780  http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/928295.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217004527/http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/928295.html |date=17 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>\uc601\ud654 '\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9', \uad00\uad11 \ud55c\ub958\uc5d0\ub3c4 \uae30\uc5ec(?)... \uc601\ud654 '\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9' \ud22c\uc5b4 \ucf54\uc2a4 \ub4f1 \uc870\uc131 http://www.consumerwide.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=38071</ref>\n\n[[Seoul Tourism Organization]] has been criticized by South Korea's opposition party and residents of Seoul for introducing a tour route featuring filming locations and stories from the movie. The Justice Party claims that the movie became famous due to the universal recognition of global [[Economic inequality|inequality]].<ref>'\ub3fc\uc9c0\uc300\uc288\ud37c\u00b7\uc790\ud558\ubb38 \ud130\ub110 \uacc4\ub2e8'...'\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9' \uad00\uad11\ucf54\uc2a4\ub294? http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200210/99620253/1 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224011027/http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200210/99620253/1 |date=24 February 2020 }}</ref> However, it sees the development of a tourist attraction based on the film in Seoul as amounting to the further exploitation of poverty.<ref>\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9 '\uad00\uad11\uc9c0 \uac1c\ubc1c' \uacbd\uc7c1\uc5d0...\"\uac00\ub09c \ubcf4\uc5ec\uc8fc\uc790\uace0?\" \uc8fc\ubbfc \ud55c\uc228\ub3c4  http://news.jtbc.joins.com/article/article.aspx?news_id=NB11935412</ref> Residents living in ''Parasite''<nowiki/>'s filming locations have reportedly complained of a sense of embarrassment and discomfort due to an increase in tourists visiting their neighborhoods and taking photos of their surroundings, making them feel like \"monkeys in a zoo\".<ref>'\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9 \ucd2c\uc601 \ub3fc\uc9c0\uc288\ud37c \ub3d9\ub124 \"\uac00\ub09c \uad6c\uacbd\ub0ac\ub098\uc694\" https://www.hankookilbo.com/News/Read/202002152060093417 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224011312/https://www.hankookilbo.com/News/Read/202002152060093417 |date=24 February 2020 }}</ref> In response, the local government of Seoul has announced that government funding will prioritize the estimated 1500 low-income families living in the semi-basement type accommodations featured in the film.<ref>`\uae30\uc0dd\ucda9`\uc21f\uac00\ub77d \uc5b9\ub294 \uc11c\uc6b8\uc2dc...\uac11\uc790\uae30 \ubc18\uc9c0\ud558 \uc9c0\uc6d0: https://www.mk.co.kr/news/realestate/view/2020/02/168236/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224015514/https://www.mk.co.kr/news/realestate/view/2020/02/168236/ |date=24 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|South Korea|Film}}\n* [[List of accolades received by Parasite|List of accolades received by ''Parasite'']]\n* [[List of submissions to the 92nd Academy Awards for Best International Feature Film]]\n* [[List of South Korean submissions for the Academy Award for Best International Feature Film]]\n* [[List of films considered the best]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{official site|https://www.madmanfilms.com.au/parasite|Australia and New Zealand official site}}\n* {{official site|https://www.parasite-movie.com|United States and Canada official site}}\n* {{official site|https://www.parasitemovie.co.uk|United Kingdom and Ireland official site}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n* {{hancinema film}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{KMDb film}} {{in lang|en}}\n* {{Mojo title}}\n* {{Metacritic film}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes}}\