{"title_page": "Bockenheim (Frankfurt am Main)", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n|name         = Bockenheim \n|type         = [[Stadtteil]]\n|Town         = Frankfurt am Main\n|image_coa    = Wappen_Frankfurt-Bockenheim.png\n|coordinates  = {{coord|50|07|26|N|08|38|21|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan   = Frankfurt Stadtteil Bockenheim.svg\n|plantext     = Location of Bockenheim (''red'') and the Ortsbezirk Innenstadt II (''light red'') within Frankfurt am Main\n|state        = Hessen\n|region       = Darmstadt \n|district     = urban\n|elevation    = \n|area         = 5.401\n|population   = 33067\n|population_as_of = 2007-12-31\n|postal_code  = 60486, 60487\n|area_code    = 069\n|licence      = F\n|website      = [http://www.frankfurt.de/sis/sis/detail.php?id=1672 www.frankfurt.de]\n}}\n'''Bockenheim''' is a city district of [[Frankfurt am Main]], [[Germany]]. It is part of the ''[[Ortsbezirk (Frankfurt am Main)|Ortsbezirk]] Innenstadt II''.\n\nBockenheim lies west of central Frankfurt and is the third largest district by population in Frankfurt after [[Sachsenhausen (Frankfurt am Main)|Sachsenhausen]] and the [[Nordend (Frankfurt am Main)|Nordend]] with approximately 35,000 inhabitants.\n\nBockenheim is bordered by the [[Johann Wolfgang Goethe University of Frankfurt am Main|Goethe University]], the [[Naturmuseum Senckenberg|Senckenberg museum]] and the [[Frankfurt Trade Fair]] in the south. The [[Bockenheimer Depot]] was the central tram depot, built around 1900, which is now a theatre, a venue of the [[St\u00e4dtische B\u00fchnen Frankfurt]]. Bockenheim also houses the global headquarters of the [[Deutsche Bundesbank|Hesse Bundesbank]]\n\nIn 2019, Albert Engelhardt published a [[mystery novel]], \"Das andere Land oder Siesta am Kanakenbunker\", set in the district.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grodensky |first1=George |title=Von Bockenheimer M\u00f6rdern und Milieus |url=https://www.fr.de/frankfurt/bockenheim-ort54494/bockenheimer-moerdern-milieus-13643000.html |work=fr.de |date=6 April 2020 |language=de}}</ref>\n\n{{Commons category|Frankfurt-Bockenheim|Bockenheim (Frankfurt am Main)}}\n{{Suburbs of Frankfurt am Main}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Districts of Frankfurt]]\n\n\n{{Hesse-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|name         = Bockenheim \n|type         = [[Stadtteil]]\n|Town         = Frankfurt am Main\n|image_coa    = Wappen_Frankfurt-Bockenheim.png\n|coordinates  = {{coord|50|07|26|N|08|38|21|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan   = Frankfurt Stadtteil Bockenheim.svg\n|plantext     = Location of Bockenheim (''red'') and the Ortsbezirk Innenstadt II (''light red'') within Frankfurt am Main\n|state        = Hessen\n|region       = Darmstadt \n|district     = urban\n|elevation    = \n|area         = 5.401\n|population   = 33067\n|population_as_of = 2007-12-31\n|postal_code  = 60486, 60487\n|area_code    = 069\n|licence      = F\n|website      = [http://www.frankfurt.de/sis/sis/detail.php?id=1672 www.frankfurt.de]\n}}\n'''Bockenheim''' is a city district of [[Frankfurt am Main]], [[Germany]]. It is part of the ''[[Ortsbezirk (Frankfurt am Main)|Ortsbezirk]] Innenstadt II''.\n\nBockenheim lies west of central Frankfurt and is the third largest district by population in Frankfurt after [[Sachsenhausen (Frankfurt am Main)|Sachsenhausen]] and the [[Nordend (Frankfurt am Main)|Nordend]] with approximately 35,000 inhabitants.\n\nBockenheim is bordered by the [[Johann Wolfgang Goethe University of Frankfurt am Main|Goethe University]], the [[Naturmuseum Senckenberg|Senckenberg museum]] and the [[Frankfurt Trade Fair]] in the south. The [[Bockenheimer Depot]] was the central tram depot, built around 1900, which is now a theatre, a venue of the [[St\u00e4dtische B\u00fchnen Frankfurt]]. Bockenheim also houses the global headquarters of the [[Deutsche Bundesbank|Hesse Bundesbank]]\n\nIn 2019, Albert Engelhardt published a [[mystery novel]], \"Das andere Land oder Siesta am Kanakenbunker\", set in the district.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grodensky |first1=George |title=Von Bockenheimer M\u00f6rdern und Milieus |url=https://www.fr.de/frankfurt/bockenheim-ort54494/bockenheimer-moerdern-milieus-13643000.html |work=https://www.fr.de |date=6 April 2020 |language=de}}</ref>\n\n{{Commons category|Frankfurt-Bockenheim|Bockenheim (Frankfurt am Main)}}\n{{Suburbs of Frankfurt am Main}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Districts of Frankfurt]]\n\n\n{{Hesse-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kahtar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repair CS1 error(s), replaced: work=https://www. \u2192 work=", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bockenheim_(Frankfurt_am_Main)"}
{"title_page": "Peeters (publishing company)", "text_new": "{{Infobox publisher\n| name         =  Peeters Publishers \n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| parent       = \n| status       = \n| traded_as    = \n| predecessor  = \n| founded      = 1857\n| founder      = <!-- or | founders = -->\n| successor    = \n| country      = Belgium\n| headquarters = [[Leuven]]\n| distribution = ISD (US)<br>VRIN (France)<br>John Garratt Publishing (Australia)\n| keypeople    = \n| publications = Books, journals, and databases\n| topics       = \n| genre        = \n| imprints     = \n| revenue      = \n| owner        = \n| numemployees = \n| website      = {{URL|http://www.peeters-leuven.be}}\n}}\n\n[https://www.peeters-leuven.be/index.php Peeters Publishers] were founded in 1857 in Belgium and became a renowned international publishing house based in Leuven. To be well represented in the international field of academic publishing they also have offices in Paris and Bristol (CT/US).\n\nPeeters is a family business, still managed and owned by the family. From the beginning, the publishing house aimed to serve the academic world by producing high-quality scholarly books. Peeters publishes around 150 titles and 40 reviews a year. Humanities and social sciences are the main fields of the publishing house with series focusing on Bible studies, Religious, Patristic, Classical and Oriental studies, Egyptology, Philosophy, Ethics, Medieval studies, and Art.\n\nTo maintain high quality in production, Peeters has its own printing business based in Belgium. There is also a Peeters Bookshop in the city center of Leuven, where scholars from all over the world come to consult a broad selection of academic books. \n\nAll Peeters publications are peer-reviewed and verified by multiple board members of the different series as well as by the editorial staff. Peeters strives to contribute to the progress of scientific research by building a network of relations established in the academic world. By producing high-quality scholarly books, Peeters try to serve academics around the world in expanding their knowledge and allowing them to share their expertise.\n==See also==\n*[https://poj.peeters-leuven.be/content.php List of Peeters' academic journals]\n*[https://www.peeters-leuven.be/search_results.php?filter=books_series List of Peeters' series]\n\n==External links==\n\n*{{Official website|http://www.peeters-leuven.be/}}\n\n[[Category:Academic publishing companies]]\n[[Category:1857 establishments in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1857]]\n\n\n{{publish-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox publisher\n| name         =  Peeters Publishers \n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| parent       = \n| status       = \n| traded_as    = \n| predecessor  = \n| founded      = 1857\n| founder      = <!-- or | founders = -->\n| successor    = \n| country      = Belgium\n| headquarters = [[Leuven]]\n| distribution = ISD (US)<br>VRIN (France)<br>John Garratt Publishing (Australia)\n| keypeople    = \n| publications = Books, journals, and databases\n| topics       = \n| genre        = \n| imprints     = \n| revenue      = \n| owner        = \n| numemployees = \n| website      = {{URL|http://www.peeters-leuven.be}}\n}}\n\n[https://www.peeters-leuven.be/index.php Peeters Publishers] were founded in 1857 in Belgium and became a renowned international publishing house based in Leuven. To be well represented in the international field of academic publishing they also have offices in Paris and Bristol (CT/US).\n\nPeeters is a family business, still managed and owned by the family. From the beginning, the publishing house aimed to serve the academic world by producing high-quality scholarly books. Peeters publishes around 150 titles and 40 reviews a year. Humanities and social sciences are the main fields of the publishing house with series focusing on Bible studies, Religious, Patristic, Classical and Oriental studies, Egyptology, Philosophy, Ethics, Medieval studies, and Art.\n\nTo maintain high quality in production, Peeters has its own printing business based in Belgium. There is also a Peeters Bookshop in the city center of Leuven, where scholars from all over the world come to consult a broad selection of academic books. \n\nAll Peeters publications are peer-reviewed and verified by multiple board members of the different series as well as by the editorial staff. Peeters strives to contribute to the progress of scientific research by building a network of relations established in the academic world. By producing high-quality scholarly books, Peeters try to serve academics around the world in expanding their knowledge and allowing them to share their expertise.\n==See also==\n* [[:Category:Peeters Publishers academic journals|List of Peeters' academic journals]]\n*[https://www.peeters-leuven.be/search_results.php?filter=books_series List of Peeters' series]\n\n==External links==\n\n*{{Official website|http://www.peeters-leuven.be/}}\n\n[[Category:Academic publishing companies]]\n[[Category:1857 establishments in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1857]]\n\n\n{{publish-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "PeetersPublishers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peeters_(publishing_company)"}
